<ArticleLayout
  title="Laundry Tub Storage That Works Around Pipes"
  description="Use the cupboard under a laundry tub without hiding leaks, blocking pipes or forcing tall bottles around awkward plumbing."
  category="Laundry"
  faqs={faqs}
  date="Updated July 2026"
  dateModified="2026-07-23"
  readingTime="6 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/laundry.webp"
  imageAlt="A practical laundry room with warm finishes, baskets and tidy everyday storage"
>
  <p>
    The cupboard under a laundry tub is not an empty rectangle. Pipes cross the middle, hoses
    claim the back corners and a hinge can make the opening narrower than the cabinet itself.
    Deep inside, a slow leak may be easier to miss than a bottle of cleaner.
  </p>
  <p>
    Empty the space and open both doors fully. Look for damp patches, staining, swelling or a
    musty smell before measuring anything. Plumbing should remain visible and reachable; storage
    has to fit around it rather than treating it as wasted space.
  </p>
  <p>
    Removable trays and baskets often make more sense here than a complex fixed organiser. They
    let the household reach bottles at the back and clear the cupboard quickly when plumbing
    needs inspection or repair.
  </p>
  <p>
    For broader laundry planning, see our main guide:{" "}
    <a href="/guides/laundry-storage-what-to-measure-and-check-before-you-buy/">
      Laundry Storage That Keeps Everyday Items Within Reach</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Inspect before you organise</h2>
  <p>
    Remove every product, loose cloth and piece of packaging. With the cabinet empty and dry,
    check the floor, side panels, back and pipe connections for:
  </p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>water marks, drips or damp residue</li>
    <li>swollen, soft or discoloured cabinet material</li>
    <li>rust, mould-like spotting or a persistent musty smell</li>
    <li>hoses rubbing against sharp edges or stored items</li>
    <li>product leaks around caps and bottle bases</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If there is active leaking, unexplained dampness or cabinet damage, leave the space clear
    and arrange appropriate attention before adding storage. A tray can contain minor bottle
    residue; it is not a repair for plumbing or water entry.
  </p>

  <h2>Draw the pipework, not just the cabinet</h2>
  <p>
    Outside dimensions give a misleading idea of capacity. Sketch the inside front-on and from
    above, then record:
  </p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>clear internal width, depth and height</li>
    <li>the lowest point of the pipework</li>
    <li>each pipe's distance from the sides and back</li>
    <li>hoses, fittings or shut-off points that need clearance</li>
    <li>usable pockets in front of and beside the plumbing</li>
    <li>the clear door opening after hinges and any centre stile</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The opening is often the tightest measurement. Test the proposed basket dimensions against
    the path through the doors, not only the space where it will sit. Anything stored at the
    back should lift out without scraping a fitting or requiring the cupboard to be unloaded.
  </p>

  <h2>Measure what will live there</h2>
  <p>
    The tallest detergent bottle, spray trigger, caddy handle and small bucket define the useful
    shelf heights. Keep liquid products upright and allow enough room to grasp and lift them.
  </p>
  <p>
    The under-tub cupboard is best reserved for a small, related group of supplies that suit the
    conditions. Depending on the household, that may include detergent, stain remover, gloves,
    dry cloths, brushes or a portable cleaning caddy. Paper goods, electrical items, food, pet
    food and moisture-sensitive belongings are better kept elsewhere.
  </p>
  <p>
    Cleaning chemicals need to remain in their original labelled containers and be stored as
    directed. Low cupboards are readily accessible, so consider whether children or pets make a
    secure alternative necessary. The guide to{" "}
    <a href="/guides/cleaning-product-storage-what-to-check-before-buying-cabinets-or-caddies/">
      cleaning product storage</a> covers this in more detail.
  </p>

  <h2>Choose organisers that clear out quickly</h2>
  <div class="advice-stack">
    <section>
      <h3>Removable basket</h3>
      <p>
        Groups items that are used together and brings the back of the cabinet forward. Choose a
        wipeable basket that clears the hinges and keeps every bottle upright.
      </p>
    </section>
    <section>
      <h3>Freestanding shelf</h3>
      <p>
        Uses clear height beside the pipes. Check stability, bottle lift-out space and whether
        the shelf can be removed without disturbing the plumbing.
      </p>
    </section>
    <section>
      <h3>Shallow tray</h3>
      <p>
        Makes minor bottle drips easier to spot and clean. It should lift out independently and
        leave the cabinet floor and pipework visible during routine checks.
      </p>
    </section>
    <section>
      <h3>Pull-out system</h3>
      <p>
        Can improve access in a deep cupboard, but the runner path must clear pipes, hinges and
        the centre opening. Fixed systems also need permission in a rental.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>

  <h2>Leave a service path</h2>
  <p>
    Do not pack products against pipes or bend hoses around an organiser. Taps, fittings and
    connections should remain visible where the cabinet design allows, and the whole area should
    be capable of being cleared without dismantling a storage system.
  </p>
  <p>
    A useful setup usually occupies the clear side pockets and leaves space beneath vulnerable
    connections. If an organiser covers the whole cabinet floor or hides the back completely,
    it makes routine inspection harder.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep damp tools out of closed baskets</h2>
  <p>
    Used cloths, brushes and mop heads may carry moisture into the cabinet. Give them somewhere
    to dry before they are enclosed with bottles. Clean, fully dry cloths can return to a
    separate basket; damp tools should not be buried where they mask leaks or make musty
    conditions harder to notice.
  </p>
  <p>
    Smooth trays and open plastic baskets are generally easier to wipe than absorbent fabric or
    untreated materials in this position. Whatever the material, remove it periodically and
    inspect the cabinet beneath it.
  </p>

  <h2>Make rental storage reversible</h2>
  <p>
    Loose trays, baskets, caddies and freestanding shelves can be cleaned, removed and taken to
    another home. Screw-fixed runners, adhesive racks and door-mounted systems need closer checks
    for permission, fit and possible surface damage.
  </p>
  <p>
    An organiser designed around one unusual set of pipes may have little value at the next
    address. For a rental, a small collection of adaptable pieces is usually easier to justify.
    The guide to{" "}
    <a href="/guides/small-laundry-storage-what-to-check-before-buying-organisers/">
      small laundry storage</a> provides more options for tight rooms.
  </p>

  <h2>Know when to leave the cupboard alone</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>there is an active leak, dampness or unexplained cabinet damage</li>
    <li>an organiser would block fittings or hose movement</li>
    <li>baskets cannot pass through the clear door opening</li>
    <li>bottles would have to lie on their sides</li>
    <li>the only available storage would be accessible to children</li>
    <li>most of the contents are empty, duplicate or belong elsewhere</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Sometimes the cupboard becomes useful as soon as it is emptied and cleaned. Do not buy an
    organiser merely to preserve products the household does not use.
  </p>

  <h2>Check it open, closed and ready to clear</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>confirm the cabinet is dry before storing anything</li>
    <li>map pipes, hoses, hinges and the true opening</li>
    <li>measure bottles upright and include lift-out room</li>
    <li>keep plumbing visible and serviceable</li>
    <li>choose removable, wipeable pieces where practical</li>
    <li>store chemicals according to their labels and household access risks</li>
    <li>keep damp tools out until they have dried</li>
    <li>make sure the cabinet can be emptied quickly</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Under-tub storage works when it fits the irregular spaces around the plumbing and still lets
    the household see what is happening behind the bottles.
  </p>

  <RelatedGuidesBlock guides={relatedGuides} />
</ArticleLayout>
